### 401 Unauthorized vs 403 Forbidden — the critical difference
Despite the name 'Unauthorized', **401** actually means **unauthenticated**: the server doesn't know who you are (no session, expired token, missing credentials). The right user action is to log in.

**403 Forbidden** means **authenticated but not authorised**: the server knows who you are, but your account doesn't have permission to perform this action. Logging in again won't help — you need a different account, or an admin to grant you the role.

| Code | Meaning | User action |
|---|---|---|
| 401 | Not authenticated | Log in |
| 403 | Not authorised | Contact admin / use a different account |

Showing a 'sign in' prompt on 403 is confusing and breaks the UX for users who are already signed in.

### Why error messages must match the user action
A well-designed error message tells the user what went wrong and what to do about it:
- **401**: 'Your session has expired. Please sign in again.' (and redirect to /login)
- **403**: 'You don't have permission to view this page. Contact your administrator if you believe this is a mistake.'
- **404**: 'This resource doesn't exist or has been removed.'
- **500**: 'Something went wrong on our end. Please try again later.'

Showing raw status codes (`HTTP 403`) or incorrect actions (`sign in` for 403) leads to support tickets and user frustration.

### Implementation pattern
```js
if (r.status === 401) {
  // Redirect to login or show 'session expired'
  router.push('/login');
  return;
}
if (r.status === 403) {
  setError("You don't have permission to do this.");
  return;
}
if (!r.ok) {
  setError(`Something went wrong (${r.status}). Please try again.`);
  return;
}
// 2xx
const data = await r.json();
```

